# Reference accessed: 2026-05-31 via gh api.
#
# tawk is an **awk implementation in Tcl** with CSV
# support and safe-mode script execution.  Reads
# patterns/actions written in Tcl rather than awk
# syntax, runs them against each line of input.
# Pivots from R292 emqtt (Erlang `getopt:parse`) into
# the **Tcl language tooling cluster**.  Sister tools:
# tclsh (Tcl shell), wish (Tk shell), tcllib (Tcl
# stdlib), Tcl::Tk (CPAN wrapper).  **MAJOR
# MILESTONE**: corpus's **first documented Tcl
# `cmdline::getoptions`-based CLI** — adds Tcl
# `cmdline` (tcllib's standard CLI library) to the
# cross-language CLI taxonomy (32 library variants
# now).
#
# Critical extraction note: tawk uses **Tcl
# `cmdline::getoptions`** at tawk:493 — tcllib's
# canonical CLI library (`package require cmdline`).
# `cmdline::getoptions argv $options $usage` MUTATES
# `argv` in-place (Tcl pass-by-name via variable
# name), removing the parsed flags and leaving the
# remaining positionals.  Returns a Tcl dict (assoc
# list) of parsed params, here unpacked via `array
# set params [...]`.  Documents the **MUTATING-argv
# parser pattern** — distinct from R287 Nim
# `parseopt` (iterator), R288 Zig `argsAlloc`
# (returns slice), R289 D `std.getopt` (mutates args
# via `ref`), R291 CL `command-line-arguments`
# (dispatch via funcall), and R292 Erlang
# `getopt:parse` (returns `{ok, {Opts, _Args}}`
# tuple).  Tcl mutates the variable named by the
# CALLER's string — uplevel semantics.  Corpus's
# **first documented mutating-argv-by-name CLI**.
#
# Critical extraction note: tawk uses **Tcl LIST-of-
# LISTS option spec** at tawk:480-489 — `set options
# { {f.arg "" "..."} {F.arg whitespace "..."} ... }`
# is a Tcl LIST whose elements are themselves LISTS.
# Each inner list is `{NAME[.arg] [DEFAULT] HELP}`:
#   - `{f.arg "" "Filename to load instead..."}`
#     → -f takes argument; default "" (empty); the
#     `.arg` suffix is a CONVENTION decoded by
#     cmdline that marks "this option takes a value"
#   - `{csv "Input is CSV data."}` → -csv boolean
#     flag (no `.arg` suffix, no default)
#   - `{F.arg whitespace "Field separator."}` → -F
#     takes argument; default "whitespace"
# Documents the **`.arg`-suffix-as-takes-value
# pattern** — distinct from R292 Erlang's 5-tuple
# with separate ArgSpec field, R291 CL plist
# `:type X :optional t`, R290 Racket's `#:args
# (fname problem)`.  The `.arg` suffix is a STRING
# CONVENTION embedded in the option name itself —
# corpus's **first string-suffix-as-type-marker CLI**.
#
# Critical extraction note: tawk uses **Tcl
# `try`/`trap` for parser error recovery** at
# tawk:552-554 — `try { ... } trap {CMDLINE USAGE}
# {msg _} { puts stderr $msg; exit 0 } on error
# {msg} { puts stderr "Error: $msg"; exit 1 }`.
# `cmdline::getoptions` raises a Tcl error with
# error-code `{CMDLINE USAGE}` when -? / --help is
# passed OR when parsing fails.  Tcl's `try`/`trap`
# matches errors by ERROR CODE (a Tcl list pattern),
# not by exception class.  Documents the **error-code-
# list trap pattern** — distinct from Python's
# `argparse.ArgumentError`, Ruby's
# `OptionParser::ParseError`, and Java picocli's
# `ParameterException`.  Tcl error codes are
# STRUCTURED LISTS (e.g., `{CMDLINE USAGE}`,
# `{POSIX ENOENT}`) used for pattern matching.
# Corpus's **first documented error-code-list trap
# CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: tawk uses **safe-interp
# script execution** at tawk:498-501 — `if
# {[info exists params(safe)] && $params(safe)} {
# set i [interp create -safe] }` — the `safe` flag
# creates a SANDBOXED Tcl interpreter (`interp
# create -safe`) for executing the user's script.
# Tcl's safe interp removes dangerous commands
# (`file`, `exec`, `socket`, etc.) and restricts I/O.
# Documents the **CLI-flag-controlled sandbox
# pattern** — convergent with `nodejs --experimental-
# permission` and Lua `5.1` sandbox-via-setfenv, but
# UNIQUE in being a FIRST-CLASS BUILT-IN of the host
# language.  No other CLI in the corpus exposes
# safe-interp sandbox-creation as a top-level CLI
# flag.  Corpus's **first sandbox-via-CLI-flag**.
#
# Critical extraction note: tawk uses **interp time
# limit** at tawk:503-506 — `if {$params(timeout) >
# 0} { interp limit $i time -seconds [expr {[clock
# seconds] + $params(timeout)}] }` — the `-timeout
# N` flag sets a WALL-CLOCK TIME LIMIT on the
# sandboxed interp via `interp limit $i time
# -seconds DEADLINE`.  When exceeded, the interp is
# torn down with a `LIMIT TIME` error.  Documents the
# **CLI-driven wall-clock interp limit pattern** —
# distinct from R268 `timeout(1)` external-process
# alarm and from RLIMIT-based shell `ulimit`.  Tcl's
# `interp limit` is INTERP-INTERNAL — the runtime
# tracks deadlines per-interp, not per-process.
# Corpus's **first documented interp-internal time-
# limit CLI**.
#
# Critical extraction note: tawk uses **CSV mode with
# quote-char and quote-policy flags** at tawk:483-485/
# 513-525 — `-csv` enables CSV input parsing, `-
# quotechar X` overrides default `"` (the BACKSLASH-
# QUOTE in the Tcl source `quotechar.arg \"` is the
# default value), and `-quoteall` switches CSV-output
# policy from `auto` to `always`.  Documents the
# **mode-flag-plus-policy-flag pattern** — `-csv` is
# the MODE switch, `-quotechar`/`-quoteall` are the
# POLICY tuners that only apply when mode is active.
# Distinct from `cat` lack-of-mode-flags and from
# `jq`'s implicit JSON-as-default mode.  tawk
# validates `quotechar` length at runtime (`if
# {[string length $params(quotechar)] != 1}`) —
# typical of stringly-typed CLI flags in dynamic
# languages.
#
# Hunt-skip notes: skipped `_pebble` (already in
# corpus + blacklisted), `_piaware` (FlightAware ADS-B
# receiver, blacklisted), `_pirehose` (FlightAware
# data hose tool, niche).  Probed tcllib's
# `modules/yaml/yaml.tcl` (library, not a CLI),
# Hog-CERN (CERN FPGA tooling, too niche), various
# Altera/Quartus FPGA tcl scripts (vendor build
# scripts, not real CLIs), ActiveState/tdk
# `tclapp.tcl` (proprietary Tcl Dev Kit).  Chose
# tawk: standalone Tcl awk-in-Tcl tool, 8 distinct
# options with EVERY major cmdline pattern variant
# (.arg-with-default, .arg-no-default, boolean,
# default-with-backslash-escape), well-documented
# usage line, and `cmdline::getoptions` invocation
# is unambiguous (single call, clean param dispatch).

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line

# 8 flags decoded source-direct from tawk:480-489
# (set options { ... } list-of-lists spec).
_arguments -s -S \
  '-f+[load script from file instead of command-line argument]:script file:_files' \
  '-F+[field separator (default: whitespace)]:separator:' \
  '-csv[input is CSV data (enables -quotechar / -quoteall)]' \
  '-quoteall[always quote CSV output fields (default: auto-quote when needed)]' \
  '-quotechar+[CSV quote character (default: double-quote; must be 1 char)]:char:' \
  '-safe[execute script in safe-mode sandboxed Tcl interpreter]' \
  '-timeout+[abort script if it runs longer than N seconds (0=no limit)]:seconds:' \
  '-version[print tawk version and exit]' \
  '-?[show usage and exit]' \
  '--help[show usage and exit]' \
  '*: :_files'
